firstly op, please dont use seafoam. its awful for your car.
but some things that i think can help you with diagnosis are:
make absolutely sure its coming from the engine and not the transmission. when you said that it revs and hiccups when changing gears, its worth double checking this. you can use a screwdriver held to your hear and up against different parts of the drivetrain to listen where the sound is loudest.

if you can eliminate the transmission as a potential problem, i would follow up by noting the idle rpm and then counting the ticks. cams rotate at half the speed of the crankshaft so if your car idles at 700rpm and the noise is recorded 6 times a second instead of 12, then you can infer that the noise is coming from the valvetrain instead of the bottom end.

based on what you said, it sounds like an issue that is not related to the bottom end but its worth checking to eliminate that as a potential issue.

personally, it sounds like an issue with timing to me. whether that be failing or dirty vvt/crank sensors, worn timing chain guides(my personal guess), or dirty oil that has sludged and gummed up the vvt system or the actuator for it( this seems likely based on your perception of improved acceleration after the atf was put in).

i would start by thinking about how well you maintain it. if you havent been changing the oil often enough i would start but pulling the oil cap off and usinga flashlight to see how it looks under the valve cover. if its all sludgy and gross, theres your place to start. i would still remove the vvt sensor and solenoids and check those for contaminants as thats easy to do and if its the issue, is an easy fix.

whatever the issue is, it isnt a significant enough of a failure to set a CEL so youll be hard pressed to find the problem without forcing the car to throw a light. one thing you can do is just load up the ignition system by putting it in high gear and flooring at slow speed.
